<p>Deeper on Mindfulness </p>
<p>
The best (but not introductory) text on the science of mindfulness may be UCLA psychiatrist
Daniel Siegel's book, 
<a href="http://drdansiegel.com/books/the_mindful_brain/">The Mindful Brain</a>.
Here is my <a href="http://www.thenewhumanism.org/authors/rick-heller/articles/the-mindful-brain">interview of Daniel Siegel</a>. 
Siegel's model of mindfulness is based in part of the ideas of 
Jeff Hawkins, author of the book 
<a href="http://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=Qg2dmntfxmQC&oi=fnd&pg=PA1&dq=jeff+hawkins&ots=6ixrJbKrhU&sig=xcjFYQ0_t-CMsaShqwWXaoRjJJs#v=onepage&q&f=false">On Intelligence</a>.
Hawkins' view of the brain is based on models of how the brain works by cognitive scientists such as
<a href="http://cns-web.bu.edu/~steve/">Stephen Grossberg</a>, who I have interviewed for a piece not yet published.
</p>

<p>
In essence, the world around us presents us with a kaleidoscope of information, and our brain filters out
much of it. This can be a good thing, but sometimes the brain does this all too well, which can lead to a 
sense of boredom. Mindfulness lowers our guards and promotes the flow of sensory information from the environment 
the brain in a very literal way,
amplifying nerve signals coming from the senses.
We notice things we may have shut out. This produces a sense of freshness, novelty and even wonder
that gets our dopamine system going and makes the world feel especially rewarding.
</p>


