<p>Deeper on Mental Noting (2 min. 43 sec.)</p>
<iframe title="YouTube video player" width="480" height="390" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/gtr_0ppOcqc" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>
<p>
Mental noting would seem to be a form of

<a href="http://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=articulatory+suppression&hl=en&as_sdt=1%2C22&as_sdtp=on">articulatory suppression</a>

  and as a form of subvocal speech, would tend to monopolize the 
<a href = "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baddeley's_model_of_working_memory">phonological loop of working memory</a>,
thereby crowding out other thoughts. Preventing the subvocal articulation of thoughts about the past or future 
would anchor one in the present moment.
</p>

<p>
The practice of silently noting one's smallest movements seems to go back to the historical Buddha's sayings, as collected in the
<a href="http://www.accesstoinsight.org/lib/authors/nyanasatta/wheel019.html#found">Foundations of Mindfulness</a>. 
Seeing the Roses does not consider the Buddha or anyone else to be authoritative, but this particular idea
seems to have a physiological basis.
</p>
